SIMPLE: macerate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Macerate
<hw>Mac"er*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Macerated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Macerating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>maceratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>macerare</ets> to make soft, weaken,
enervate; cf. Gr. <?/ to knead.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make lean; to
cause to waste away.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Harvey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To subdue the appetites of by poor and scanty diet;
to mortify.</def> <rj><au>Baker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To soften by steeping in a liquid, with or without
heat; to wear away or separate the parts of by steeping; <as>as, to
<ex>macerate</ex> animal or vegetable fiber</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macerater</ent>⟦br⟧
